    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1918-05-31T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1918-05-31T00:00:00-05:00" n="534"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d534">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 861.00/2078</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Consul General at London</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Skinner</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">No. 6230</seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">London</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1918-05-31">
                            <hi rend="italic">May 31, 1918</hi>
                        </date>. <lb/> [<hi rend="italic">Received June 20.</hi>]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: I have the honor to transmit herewith a pamphlet
                    entitled, <hi rend="italic">The Bolshevik Revolution: Its Rise and
                        Meaning</hi>,<note n="1" xml:id="d534fn1">Not printed.</note> by
                        <persName>Maxim Litvinov</persName>, <pb facs="0622" n="548" xml:id="pg_548"
                    /> the plenipotentiary of the Russian people’s government in Great Britain.</p>
                <p>This pamphlet has been much commented upon in this country as the best available
                    exposition of the subject, and I think that students of the question in the
                    Department will be very glad to have it. Unfortunately, I have only been able to
                    obtain one copy, and Mr. <persName>Litvinov</persName> tells me that the edition
                    is out of print, but he hopes to let me have a few more later on.</p>
                <p>I have [etc.]</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Robert P. Skinner</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
